# 12. Hashing, Shingling, OCR, and Merkle Trees

## 12.1 Hashing

V1 default:

> **SHA-256**

Used for:

* whole-file hashes
* shingle hashes
* object/package hashes
* manifest/package integrity

All hashes include algorithm/version metadata.

## 12.2 Whole-File Hashing

Supported across all tiers.

Free is whole-file only.

Whole-file hash leaves appear in the attestation Merkle tree.

## 12.3 Shingling

Supported for:

* Team Starter
* Team Pro
* Enterprise

Not supported for Free.

V1 shingling applies to:

* text files
* PDFs with native text
* scanned PDFs via OCR fallback

V1 shingle presets:

* `standard`
* `broad`
* `sensitive`

Presets are controlled by system templates/policy.

Shingle plaintext never leaves the desktop app.

## 12.4 OCR

V1 supports local OCR for scanned PDFs.

Engine selection:

> **Tesseract is the V1 OCR engine, version-pinned in the desktop app and recorded in the manifest.**

OCR V1 spec must evaluate two packaging paths before final implementation:

1. Native bundled Tesseract binaries
2. Tesseract.js / WASM

Evaluation criteria include Mac universal packaging, Windows x64/arm64 packaging, code signing/notarization impact, installer size, performance on large PDFs, memory use, language pack handling, confidence score behavior, and licensing.

Default preference is native bundled Tesseract; fall back to Tesseract.js only if native packaging creates unacceptable distribution risk.

Language packs:

> **English only by default in V1.** Additional language packs are post-V1 or Enterprise-configurable.

Rules:

* OCR bundled inside desktop app
* no separate dependency installation
* OCR text treated as local derived plaintext
* OCR text never uploaded
* OCR engine/version/language-pack version recorded in metadata
* confidence/warnings shown locally
* extracted text preview available locally
* no manual OCR text editing in V1
* OCR-derived shingle coverage must be visibly marked as OCR-derived in receipts

Confidence threshold:

* compute page-level mean word confidence where available
* mark page as low-confidence if mean confidence is below a numerical threshold
* starting threshold: **80%** (tunable after test-corpus evaluation)

Failure behavior:

| Scenario                                  | Behavior                                      |
| ----------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Whole-file hash succeeds, shingling fails | Include whole-file only if producer continues |
| OCR fails                                 | File can be included as whole-file only       |
| Whole-file hash fails                     | File cannot be included                       |
| Low OCR confidence                        | Warning recorded; producer may continue       |
| Failed files                              | Never silently included                       |

### OCR test corpus

Engineering assembles the initial OCR V1 test corpus from **public, non-sensitive sources**. Product/Architecture supplements later with representative real-world examples as they become available.

| Category      | Examples                                      |
| ------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Legal         | Scanned contracts, exhibits, court-style PDFs |
| Research      | Scanned papers, tables, footnotes             |
| Business docs | Invoices, memos, reports                      |
| Media/archive | Mixed-layout PDFs, captions, image-heavy docs |
| Low quality   | Skewed scans, low contrast, rotated pages     |
| Native PDFs   | Text-layer PDFs for extraction comparison     |

> **No customer or private documents are admitted to the OCR test corpus unless explicitly approved and sanitized.**

## 12.5 Merkle Tree

One canonical Merkle tree per attestation.

Leaves may include:

* whole-file hashes
* component hashes
* shingle hashes

Rules:

* deterministic leaf ordering
* leaf type/count metadata stored
* duplicate leaf detection
* server recomputes Merkle root from submitted leaves
* confirmed Merkle root becomes canonical

