## 26.1.1 Desktop Version Enforcement

Desktop app must check version compatibility against the API on launch, cache the policy locally, and honor a TTL when offline.

Default TTL for V1 pilot: **7 days** (tenant-configurable later for Enterprise).

Cached policy includes minimum supported version, recommended version, blocked versions, protocol compatibility range, fetched timestamp, expiration, upgrade URL, and release notes URL. Policy responses must be signed by Proveria and include a freshness timestamp and max-age to prevent replay of stale "allowed" responses.

| Scenario                              | Behavior                                                 |
| ------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| Online and current version allowed    | Normal operation                                         |
| Online and version below minimum      | Block submission                                         |
| Online and version explicitly blocked | Block submission                                         |
| Offline and cached policy still valid | Allow submission if cached policy allows current version |
| Offline and cached policy expired     | Allow draft viewing/export, block submission             |
| Blocked version                       | Drafts remain readable/exportable; submission blocked    |

> **Version enforcement must never destroy or strand local drafts.** Even if submission is blocked, the user must be able to open the app, view local drafts, export local draft metadata where safe, and upgrade.

## 26.2 Sequencing Principle

Build the trust spine first:

```txt
pair desktop
  → create project
  → create attestation
  → hash locally
  → submit signed manifest
  → server validates
  → confirm
  → lookup hash
  → generate proof package
  → render receipt
```

Do not build OCR before the whole-file attestation and lookup loop works.

Shingling and OCR are differentiators, but the core cryptographic attestation loop must be stable first.

